Interview Questions
1. What are selection statements in Java?
-->Selection statements are used to control the flow of execution based on conditions.
    👉 Types:
          if
          if-else
          if-else-if ladder
          switch
          
          They help the program choose one path among many.


2. Difference between if and if-else.
-->
| Feature       | if                                   | if-else                                  |
| ------------- | ------------------------------------ | ---------------------------------------- |
| Execution     | Runs block only if condition is true | Runs one block if true, another if false |
| Optional else | No                                   | Yes                                      |
| Use case      | Single condition check               | Two-way decision                         |



3. Can we use multiple if statements without else?
-->Yes ✅
    This is called independent if statements.
      if (x > 0) {
          System.out.println("Positive");
      }
      if (x % 2 == 0) {
          System.out.println("Even");
      }
    👉 Both conditions are checked separately.


4. What is an if-else-if ladder, and how does it work?
-->It is used to check multiple conditions sequentially.
      
      if (marks >= 90) {
          System.out.println("A");
      } else if (marks >= 75) {
          System.out.println("B");
      } else {
          System.out.println("C");
      }
      
      👉 Execution stops after the first true condition.



5. When should you use switch instead of if-else?
-->Use switch when:
    You compare one variable
    Against multiple constant values
    Code becomes cleaner than multiple if-else
    
    👉 Example: menu selection, days of week


6. What happens if you forget to use a break in a switch case?
-->👉 It causes fall-through  
        int x = 2;
        
        switch(x) {
            case 1:
                System.out.println("One");
            case 2:
                System.out.println("Two");
            case 3:
                System.out.println("Three");
        }
        
        👉 Output:
                Two
                Three



7. Can we use logical operators (&&, ||) in a switch expression?
-->❌ No
    Switch works only with: 
        constants
        fixed values

    👉 You cannot write conditions like:  case x > 10 && x < 20  // ❌ invalid


8. Difference between switch expression (Java 12+) and old switch statement.
-->
| Feature       | Old switch | New switch (Java 12+) |
| ------------- | ---------- | --------------------- |
| Syntax        | `case:`    | `case ->`             |
| Break needed  | Yes        | No                    |
| Fall-through  | Yes        | No (by default)       |
| Returns value | No         | Yes                   |

👉 Example (new switch):
      int result = switch(day) {
          case 1 -> 10;
          case 2 -> 20;
          default -> 0;
      };



9. Can we have duplicate case values in a switch?
-->❌ No  👉 It gives compile-time error.


10. What happens if no case matches and no default is present?
-->👉 Nothing happens
    👉 Control moves outside the switch



11. Can we use a switch with wrapper classes like Integer?
-->✅ Yes (since Java 5)
      Integer x = 10;
      
      switch(x) {
          case 10:
              System.out.println("Ten");
      }



12. Can a switch statement work on enum types?
-->✅ Yes  
    enum Day { MON, TUE }
    
    Day d = Day.MON;
    
    switch(d) {
        case MON:
            System.out.println("Monday");
    }




13. What is the fall-through behavior in a switch?
-->👉 When break is missing, execution continues to next cases.
      
      case 1:
      case 2:
          System.out.println("1 or 2");
      
      👉 Used intentionally to group cases.
